WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:16.639
Hey there! Welcome to the Paws at Data Science Hangout. I'm Libby Herron, and this is a recording

00:00:16.639 --> 00:00:21.840
of our weekly community call that happens every Thursday at 12 p.m. U.S. Eastern Time.

00:00:21.840 --> 00:00:26.719
If you are not joining us live, you miss out on the amazing chat that's going on,

00:00:26.719 --> 00:00:30.879
so find the link in the description where you can add our call to your calendar and come hang out

00:00:30.879 --> 00:00:36.560
with the most supportive, friendly, and funny data community you'll ever experience. I can't wait to

00:00:36.560 --> 00:00:42.320
see you there. I am so excited to be joined by our featured leader today, Harvey Lieberman,

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:48.880
Associate Director of Data Science at Novartis. Hello Harvey, how are you doing today? I'm doing

00:00:48.880 --> 00:00:54.880
good, thanks Libby, thanks for having me. Oh we're so happy to have you here. If you are a part of

00:00:55.599 --> 00:01:00.080
our pharma community, you probably already know Harvey. Harvey, I would love it if you could

00:01:00.080 --> 00:01:03.680
introduce yourself, tell us a little bit about yourself and your background, and what you like

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:12.480
to do for fun. Sure, so my name is Harvey Lieberman. I work in the pharma industry,

00:01:13.440 --> 00:01:26.400
have done for 27 years now, it's a long time, and I'm a data scientist. I've worked in both

00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:31.040
the discovery setting and the development setting, and I'm sure we'll go into a little bit

00:01:31.040 --> 00:01:41.199
about that as we chat a little bit more. For fun, I guess I'm what you would call

00:01:41.279 --> 00:01:50.080
a little bit of a geek, because I like to do data science for fun as well as for work.

00:01:51.279 --> 00:01:57.839
I also have three kids and spend a lot of time with them, shuttling them around,

00:01:57.839 --> 00:02:03.120
doing different things, and so on. But yeah, that's pretty much it for me.

00:02:03.519 --> 00:02:09.039
I think that you'll find that you're in a big group of other geeks.

00:02:10.800 --> 00:02:18.240
We probably identify with you. I would love it if you could explain just a little bit of context

00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:24.240
for us so that we can all ask questions that are informed by knowledge. What is Novartis?

00:02:25.039 --> 00:02:28.720
What does Novartis do? And what do you do at Novartis?

00:02:29.600 --> 00:02:40.720
Okay, so Novartis is a big pharma company. I have many products out there. You've probably

00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:50.639
seen lots of ads on TV with regards to many of the products. I joined Novartis five years ago,

00:02:50.639 --> 00:02:58.160
and I'm working in a biostatistics group in drug development, in early drug development.

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:09.839
So the role that the group that I'm in has is, as drugs are moving towards the development phase

00:03:09.839 --> 00:03:15.600
and into development, which is where we're starting to test them, potentially test them

00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:24.399
in humans for the first time, we get involved. We're, I would say, data science, biostatistics,

00:03:24.399 --> 00:03:32.639
and programming, doing all the statistical work to ensure that things are working, that things are

00:03:32.639 --> 00:03:40.240
safe on what is initially the first couple of phases of drug development, which are where we

00:03:40.240 --> 00:03:51.919
have a few patients, maybe up tens or hundreds, a couple of hundreds maybe. And then that passes

00:03:51.919 --> 00:04:00.880
on to full development, where there's a lot more time involved and effort in bringing these things

00:04:00.880 --> 00:04:09.279
to the market. But prior to my role here, I was also working in drug discovery, which is where

00:04:09.279 --> 00:04:17.760
we'll do a lot of work in trying to identify the molecules that will become medicines that will

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:24.559
then move into development as well. And one last thing, there's an enormous attrition rate

00:04:24.559 --> 00:04:32.079
as you move, as you start in discovery, moving towards development. So most of the things that

00:04:32.079 --> 00:04:36.799
you work on, certainly from a discovery and early development perspective, most of the things that

00:04:36.799 --> 00:04:40.640
you work on don't make it to the market for one reason or another.

00:04:40.640 --> 00:04:46.000
Interesting. Okay. Yeah. Usually when I hear the word attrition rate, I'm used to talking to a lot of people,

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:51.279
analytics folks, and that's people leaving a company, right, is attrition, or leaving a team,

00:04:51.279 --> 00:04:56.799
leaving positions. But this is attrition of potential molecules, right? Like this is like

00:04:56.799 --> 00:05:03.519
the things that are viable, that the pool of them get less and less as you move on. Well, I wanted to

00:05:03.920 --> 00:05:11.040
let everybody know a quick little like a short list of topics that we could ask Harvey about.

00:05:11.040 --> 00:05:14.799
I've never done this before, but I think it might be helpful just to help us like build context

00:05:14.799 --> 00:05:20.239
around these questions. And that is questions about RFARMA. If you've heard about RFARMA at

00:05:20.239 --> 00:05:24.079
all, if you've been to the RFARMA conference, if you know what the RFARMA community is,

00:05:24.079 --> 00:05:30.239
or if you don't know, we can ask Harvey about that. We can also talk about Harvey's journey

00:05:31.200 --> 00:05:35.679
into data science because it is a little bit non-traditionally, doesn't have a statistics

00:05:35.679 --> 00:05:41.440
background or a computational background. And I think that there are a lot of people here who

00:05:41.440 --> 00:05:48.480
could identify with that as well. There are some questions that we could ask about career advice.

00:05:48.480 --> 00:05:54.399
Harvey's been in the field for a very, very long time. And Harvey also has a special place in his

00:05:54.399 --> 00:06:02.160
heart for automated processes and the way that that can sort of alter your career. So Harvey,

00:06:02.160 --> 00:06:06.079
I would love to just get started by asking you to describe a little bit about RFARMA

00:06:06.079 --> 00:06:09.440
and how it got started. Sure. Yeah. So

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:23.600
RFARMA is essentially a community. So becoming what is now some of a large community, I would say.

00:06:25.440 --> 00:06:35.600
We started in 2017. In 2017, our industry, the pharma industry was at a point where

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:45.519
people were starting to get interested in the use of open source. And just to caveat this,

00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:55.200
pharma traditionally has used SAS for statistical programming. And that was starting to become a

00:06:55.200 --> 00:07:05.519
movement to see, well, could R be used instead of SAS? And where could it be used? And would it be

00:07:05.519 --> 00:07:13.600
advantageous to move in these kinds of directions? So several people from multiple companies were

00:07:13.600 --> 00:07:21.920
starting to dabble in this area. And there wasn't really a forum where people could connect,

00:07:21.920 --> 00:07:30.720
could talk about it, could share information. So a few people got together through partly

00:07:30.720 --> 00:07:37.920
through Phil Boucher from Posit, which was then, back in the day, our studio, who helped

00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:42.559
pull people together, pull some like-minded people together. And we decided to put together a

00:07:42.559 --> 00:07:48.239
conference, the first one in 2018, so that people could share what they've been working on.

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:56.480
And the first conference was at Harvard University. Harvard were really nice.

00:07:56.480 --> 00:08:01.440
They gave us a space where we could use. Pulled together, there were about 150 people

00:08:02.559 --> 00:08:08.160
for two days. And it went really well. And we repeated it in 2019.

00:08:09.679 --> 00:08:17.040
And then in 2020, we were looking to make it a little bit bigger, so that more people could

00:08:17.040 --> 00:08:27.279
come, more people could share. We then came across COVID, like everyone else, and pivoted to what has

00:08:27.279 --> 00:08:34.719
since then become an online, a virtual conference. And we've just gone on from there. So

00:08:35.679 --> 00:08:43.280
we also do a face-to-face summit once a year. We try and tag this onto PositConf.

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:50.880
And really, what the group is, is it's just a large community of people who are all like-minded,

00:08:52.559 --> 00:09:00.239
want to work within open source, want to use open source within the industry. But also, I would say

00:09:00.239 --> 00:09:07.200
that it's not only people from the pharma and biotech industries. It's open to everyone.

00:09:07.200 --> 00:09:17.599
We just use this as a really a focus on some of the presentations and the tools. But really,

00:09:17.599 --> 00:09:24.080
it's a large community that's open to everyone. I love that. It's something that I tell everybody.

00:09:24.080 --> 00:09:28.320
Like, you don't have to be in pharma to go to the rPharma conference and to go to the workshops and

00:09:28.320 --> 00:09:34.400
get a lot out of them. I'm not in pharma at all. I have a business background. I attend rPharma.

00:09:34.400 --> 00:09:40.400
I go to the workshops. I watch the lectures. I mean, it's so much fun. I highly encourage

00:09:40.400 --> 00:09:44.719
everybody to go check it out. Okay, Harvey, we have so many questions coming in. Let's

00:09:44.719 --> 00:09:50.239
go ahead and start getting some questions from Slido. So the most popular question in Slido is

00:09:50.239 --> 00:09:53.919
actually, what data science projects do you do for fun? You mentioned that you do data science

00:09:53.919 --> 00:10:09.280
for funsies. What do you got? Yeah. Oh, God. So I just, I'm a big fan of R, of Python,

00:10:09.840 --> 00:10:18.479
of other languages. I'm trying, I'm teaching myself Go at the moment. So that's a fun experience.

00:10:18.960 --> 00:10:28.799
Really, it's just finding data from a day-to-day point of view and playing around with it.

00:10:28.799 --> 00:10:39.599
So we have things, obviously, things like the Tidy Tuesday. If, when it comes to December,

00:10:39.599 --> 00:10:47.200
I always try and do as much of Advent of Code as possible. If anyone does that, that's a lot of fun.

00:10:48.080 --> 00:10:57.679
Especially to learn a new language. I'm playing around with Gen AI, just like everyone else

00:10:57.679 --> 00:11:07.840
probably is, as much as possible. But trying to do it from playing with the APIs and from a

00:11:07.840 --> 00:11:15.359
programming perspective. So for example, it doesn't sound like fun, but one of the things I'm trying

00:11:15.359 --> 00:11:25.039
to do with the AI side, and I've seen this done by other people too, is to take all the information

00:11:25.039 --> 00:11:35.119
from my, from our, for example, bank and credit card statements, and give me an idea as to what

00:11:35.119 --> 00:11:44.880
we're spending and where, and how we can do better. And doing it using local LLMs, so nothing's going

00:11:44.960 --> 00:11:52.400
out. So the idea of being able to do this all locally, that's just one of the things. Plus,

00:11:52.400 --> 00:11:57.599
just little snippets of code whenever I can. I try and push them out, I try and blog them out

00:11:58.479 --> 00:12:07.200
wherever possible, because I find that it ends up as a repository that I can go back to at any point

00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:14.080
to find what I did. Which is so nice, yeah. Your GitHub turns into your own little code library.

00:12:14.880 --> 00:12:19.760
It's another thing I highly recommend. I have a banking background, and I attempt to do my own

00:12:20.479 --> 00:12:25.599
financial analysis all the time, and I'm always stumped by the messiness of sick codes. I don't

00:12:25.599 --> 00:12:30.479
know if anybody else has run into that or not, where the little code that tells you what the

00:12:30.479 --> 00:12:35.119
industry of the business is, so basically where you're spending your money, is so frustrating.

00:12:35.119 --> 00:12:40.880
Especially if you do a lot of buying through PayPal or Amazon or Chewy for pet products. A lot

00:12:40.880 --> 00:12:46.479
of things can be very confusing when they get through those filters. All right, let's do another

00:12:46.479 --> 00:12:52.400
question from Slido. These questions have been rolling in here. A big one is around SaaS,

00:12:52.400 --> 00:12:57.359
and there are several questions that kind of mention this, so let's do this one as a summary.

00:12:58.320 --> 00:13:02.239
I have a question from Gregory Power. Gregory, if you are available,

00:13:02.239 --> 00:13:06.000
I would love it if you could ask your question live. Yeah, of course.

00:13:06.799 --> 00:13:15.599
Hey! I work for a municipality in SaaS's backyard. I won't disclose which one.

00:13:20.479 --> 00:13:26.000
Anywho, yeah, how was it transitioning from SaaS, and how is it migrating from this

00:13:26.960 --> 00:13:31.760
monolith of infrastructure? Because you're talking to someone who had to restart all

00:13:31.760 --> 00:13:35.280
three of their servers this morning because our SaaS cluster went down.

00:13:38.880 --> 00:13:44.320
So I can speak probably from an, you know, somewhat from an industry perspective as opposed

00:13:44.320 --> 00:13:49.359
to an internal perspective, because we're, I would say we're going through it at the moment.

00:13:49.359 --> 00:13:54.479
Other companies have gone through it, and there are lots of companies within the industry

00:13:54.479 --> 00:14:02.400
at various stages of going through it, and lots of people are, I would say,

00:14:05.119 --> 00:14:09.200
not really stumbling along the route, but it can be a little bit challenging.

00:14:12.159 --> 00:14:19.679
I would say that within the pharma industry, if you look at some companies, for example, GSK,

00:14:20.320 --> 00:14:28.239
Roche have done a lot of work, and they've actually presented and put out a lot of work on

00:14:29.520 --> 00:14:35.679
the transition. One of the biggest challenges, I would say,

00:14:37.520 --> 00:14:42.640
rather than an infrastructure perspective, is a training perspective,

00:14:43.520 --> 00:14:49.840
especially when you've got people who have been using something like SaaS for a long time. Just

00:14:49.840 --> 00:14:56.400
the thought process of how you would approach a problem coming from more of a

00:14:58.559 --> 00:15:02.880
more traditional programming language approach is quite different.

00:15:02.880 --> 00:15:10.000
And you also, when we're looking at moving, or when we're looking as an industry, moving from

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:18.880
from SaaS to R, or transitioning SaaS to R, I would say there's more to it than that. It's more

00:15:18.880 --> 00:15:29.200
transitioning from, as you put it, a monolithic type approach to something that is,

00:15:29.919 --> 00:15:38.880
to something that is more of an open source approach, where we're not talking about just R,

00:15:38.880 --> 00:15:46.159
we're talking about using, maybe using Git, or something else for versioning,

00:15:46.159 --> 00:15:55.359
for version control, looking into where CICD can step in. So it's this concept of

00:15:55.599 --> 00:16:02.320
bringing people along who might be used to working in one way for a very long time,

00:16:02.960 --> 00:16:09.520
to what you might call more modern approaches. And that's a, it's an interesting journey to take

00:16:09.520 --> 00:16:19.840
people on. And certainly, you know, the Git concept, or the GitLab, GitHub, Bitbucket

00:16:20.640 --> 00:16:28.880
concept, when you show someone how they can do it just with their own code, how they can manage it

00:16:28.880 --> 00:16:35.760
so much better, you tend to have people coming along for this journey. So that's one of the

00:16:35.760 --> 00:16:44.320
things I'd say. I like that. It's focused on the advantages that you see on a personal level first,

00:16:44.799 --> 00:16:49.200
and then transition that into like, we could be doing this on an organizational level,

00:16:49.200 --> 00:16:56.640
or a team level, or whatever it is. It sounds like there are a lot of people in the chat who

00:16:56.640 --> 00:17:03.039
are in some way familiar with the SaaS to R, or SaaS to Python journey, or even the Stata to R,

00:17:03.039 --> 00:17:07.599
or Stata to Python journey, depending on where they're coming from. Thank you, Gregory,

00:17:07.599 --> 00:17:13.439
for that great question. I have another question from Lulu. Would you like to unmute and ask your

00:17:13.439 --> 00:17:21.359
question? And hi, Lulu. Nice to see you. Good to see you too, Libby. Thank you. So, you know,

00:17:21.359 --> 00:17:25.040
Harvey, part of your intro and part of the description for this talk is that you'd like

00:17:25.040 --> 00:17:28.959
to automate processes, you'd like to make workflows easier. And so I was curious,

00:17:28.959 --> 00:17:34.000
how is Gen AI either affecting that now? Or how is that affecting the future?

00:17:34.239 --> 00:17:44.319
Okay, so let me take a step back and give an example of an old one. Because I think we,

00:17:44.319 --> 00:17:50.800
many of us in data science, or working in data science, have probably had experiences like this.

00:17:51.119 --> 00:17:58.640
I've probably had experiences like this. So I worked in a group

00:18:01.040 --> 00:18:11.280
where I was working on a biomarker analysis. And in this one example, I had a colleague come

00:18:11.839 --> 00:18:20.079
over from Germany to visit. And he was working in a completely different group.

00:18:21.119 --> 00:18:32.640
He was working with bioreactors. And he had a setup with an experiment with 48 bioreactors.

00:18:33.359 --> 00:18:41.040
And they collected a whole bunch of data over a period of time. And they analyzed it with an Excel

00:18:41.040 --> 00:18:53.439
workbook. So he showed me an Excel workbook that had 48 sheets with data in. And the data

00:18:54.239 --> 00:19:00.800
did not start in the top left-hand corner. There was some notes coming down. And then you had

00:19:00.800 --> 00:19:09.520
tables of data for the first 48 sheets. And then the next 20 or 30 were charts that they'd made

00:19:09.520 --> 00:19:19.439
by hand. And it had taken someone about three months, I was told, to work on this.

00:19:19.520 --> 00:19:25.199
So this was an example where I could take something and say, well, we can't get the raw data,

00:19:25.199 --> 00:19:30.959
but we can pull the data out from the Excel. We can put it together in a shiny dashboard.

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:38.400
And we can just look at all the graphs and look at all the charts. And two things happen. One is,

00:19:38.400 --> 00:19:47.439
it took me one hour to do this over lunch. And secondly, it took me one hour and a half to do

00:19:48.160 --> 00:19:57.040
this. And secondly, I found mistakes in their copying and pasting of formulae from cell to cell.

00:19:58.560 --> 00:20:04.319
So as I say, it was about three months worth of work to get to this point, which could have been

00:20:04.319 --> 00:20:11.359
saved easily. And I think we've all had situations like this. And the nice thing about this is, it

00:20:11.439 --> 00:20:16.719
took someone who was a lab scientist. And actually, they went back and it turned them

00:20:16.719 --> 00:20:21.760
into a data scientist, because they started to learn R and Python to be able to do these things.

00:20:22.959 --> 00:20:27.920
This is one of the many, many examples. I hope we get to others. But to your question, Lou,

00:20:28.479 --> 00:20:34.400
how is Gen AI going to do this? How is Gen AI going to contribute to this? I think it's going

00:20:34.400 --> 00:20:40.479
to contribute hugely. I think what it's going to do is, what we've had the opportunity to do is,

00:20:40.479 --> 00:20:46.880
as data scientists in the past, is to take some of this mundane stuff and

00:20:50.880 --> 00:20:58.400
replace it with an automated process that's much more efficient, much faster. With Gen AI,

00:20:58.400 --> 00:21:03.599
we now have tools at our disposal that are going to be able to do this even more efficiently.

00:21:03.680 --> 00:21:13.040
So I know people, it goes back and forth in the conversation with Gen AI. Is it a replacement?

00:21:13.040 --> 00:21:17.920
I look at this more as a tool. This is another tool in our box that we'll be able to use.

00:21:18.479 --> 00:21:25.439
One of the nice things it will be able to do is, when you come to, say, a data automation task,

00:21:25.439 --> 00:21:30.640
we'll be able to put things in place using these kinds of tools that can check that what we've got

00:21:30.640 --> 00:21:38.719
in place is working as we expect it as well. So I see these kinds of tools really speeding up the

00:21:38.719 --> 00:21:46.479
process, really helping moving forward and becoming more robust. I like that. It reminds me of our

00:21:46.479 --> 00:21:52.719
conversation with Jay Timmerman at Biogen, where he really suggested everybody take a more practical

00:21:52.719 --> 00:21:57.920
approach to thinking about Gen AI. Like, what are these really, really sort of boring, mundane,

00:21:57.920 --> 00:22:03.359
practical things that can be fixed and improved and think of it less in a magical, sparkly way?

00:22:04.719 --> 00:22:06.800
Thank you so much, Lou, for the fantastic question.

00:22:06.800 --> 00:22:11.119
Can I just have one quick follow-up, which is, so thank you, Harvey. That was great.

00:22:11.760 --> 00:22:15.359
And I strongly agree with the point of, like, it's another tool. It's not a replacement for

00:22:15.359 --> 00:22:20.560
data science. But you mentioned the spreadsheet that had errors in it. I know everyone's shocked

00:22:20.560 --> 00:22:23.920
here that there was a complex spreadsheet with errors in it. No one has seen that before.

00:22:24.880 --> 00:22:30.079
But a lot of people are paranoid about Gen AI. So just can you comment on, in terms of when you talk

00:22:30.079 --> 00:22:34.560
trying to introduce Gen AI, is there, I mean, is there a lot of pushback from, oh no, we can't trust

00:22:34.560 --> 00:22:40.959
it because of hallucinations? Or is there more openness than that? I'd say within our company,

00:22:40.959 --> 00:22:47.839
and I'd say within the industry as a whole, people are starting to approach it. So there's caution.

00:22:47.839 --> 00:22:52.959
The pharma industry is somewhat risk averse anyway, as an industry.

00:22:54.959 --> 00:23:02.319
People are starting to use it more. It's being encouraged more to use on a day-to-day basis.

00:23:02.319 --> 00:23:10.560
And what we're seeing is that people are starting to use it to automate and to speed up some of

00:23:10.560 --> 00:23:20.400
their day-to-day work. So for example, something as simple as summarize a meeting so that I don't

00:23:20.400 --> 00:23:26.560
have to read through. And I feel that as people start to get more and more on board with that,

00:23:27.359 --> 00:23:34.479
we're going to find more and more of a move through. I feel like the industry as a whole

00:23:34.479 --> 00:23:43.920
is going to be somewhat protective of throwing all of their data into this. And I would say that

00:23:43.920 --> 00:23:53.439
most companies, you know, the few that I know working in the area have something where you've

00:23:53.439 --> 00:23:59.599
got certain business rules in place. So do not put your data into something that's going out.

00:24:00.400 --> 00:24:06.719
But utilize these kinds of things to make your day-to-day work more effective, more efficient.

00:24:07.280 --> 00:24:12.800
And that's where we are at the moment. Now, where things move in the future is, you know, we've seen

00:24:12.800 --> 00:24:18.959
so much growth within the last year or two, who can tell. But I see us getting to a point where

00:24:18.959 --> 00:24:26.560
we're going to be using the tools a lot more. I love it. Mike, I know that you have a little bit

00:24:26.560 --> 00:24:33.680
of perspective here as well. Mike is at Pfizer. Would you like to chime in? Yeah, actually, it's

00:24:33.680 --> 00:24:39.920
kind of based on what Harvey was just saying about sharing proprietary information externally

00:24:39.920 --> 00:24:48.479
